(Prosper Loan Data)¶

by (Amira Salama)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Prosper Marketplace is America's first peer-to-peer lending marketplace, with over $7 billion in funded loans,

Borrowers request personal loans on Prosper and investors (individual or institutional) can fund anywhere from USD 2000 to USD 40000 per loan request.

Investors can consider borrowers’ credit scores, ratings, and histories and the category of the loan. Prosper handles the servicing of the loan and collects and distributes borrower payments and interest back to the loan investors. wikipedia source link

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.(Last updated 03/11/2014)

This data dictionary explains the variables in the data set.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data contains 113937 observations and 81 columns, most variables (61 features) are numeric, and 20 object, bool or categorical features

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Investigating factors affecting borrower’s APR or interest rate, and loan’s outcome status

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I Suggested some of the following features would have an impact on the Borrower’s APR and the Loan Status: such as :Loan Original Amount, Prosper Score, Income Range, Borrower's Occupation, Employment Status, Credit Grade,Credit Score Range, term of the loan in months, Monthly Loan Payment.

Out[13]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='ProsperScore', ylabel='count'>

According to the data variable definition table, the prosper score is a custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009. so the highest values are between 4 and 8 which is the average score of a prosper borrower.

Loans are assigned a loan grade based on its interest rate. Each loan grade is associated with a modeled default range. The loan grades range from “AA”, which is the lowest modeled risk, to “E”, which is the highest modeled risk. so most loans have average score (C, D, B)

The Credit Score Range seem to be normally distributed around 500 to 880 score, the higher the score the more liable for a borrower to get the loan, above 70% of the scores are higher than 580 score which is the fair score or the accepted one.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The Borrower’s APR variable took on a very small range of values, I had to assign a little value for the bins to watch the distribution. the data looked normally distributed except above the values 0.31 and between 0.36 there was a large peak

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Loan Original Amount was highly right skewed and had a number of outliers , I had to increase the number of bins in the original distribution to monitor closely the change in values of the loan amount, so loans above 25K are rarely given.

Estimated return is the difference between the Estimated Effective Yield and the Estimated Loss Rate. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
